description: From Anglo-Norman, Old French resembler, from re- + sembler (“to seem”), synchronically analyzable as re- +‎ semble.

verbs.description: resemble (third-person singular simple present resembles, present participle resembling, simple past and past participle resembled)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To be like or similar to (something); to represent as similar.
examples: But what you've just described does resemble a person of that kind.

entries.meaning: (transitive, now rare, archaic) To compare; to regard as similar, to liken.

examples: They can so well resemble mans speech.

entries.meaning: (obsolete, transitive) To cause to imitate or be like; to make similar.
examples: they resemble themselves to the swans
